scripts/git_sort/lib.py: Group related code together.

There should be no difference in "object" code.

git-sort: Encapsulate patch tag operations in an object.

This allows a single read of the patch file, multiple operations (read and
write) followed by a single write.

git-sort: Set cwd when calling git.

avoids repetitive code

scripts/git_sort/lib.py: Remove section headers from series header.

Currently, if there is no mainline section, the first thing that will be
found inside the sorted patches section is a section header like
"# out-of-tree patches". It will be considered to be a comment that's part
of the series header ("# sorted patches"). Change series_header() to filter
out such section headers.

git-sort: Add a script to insert new entries in series.conf.

Specifically, to add new patches to the sorted section of series.conf.

git-sort: series_conf: Add a mode to print names only

Print patch file names from the sorted section without comments or empty
lines.

git-sort: Port to python3

Most of the changes are related to subprocess calling, encoding and str vs.
bytes.

git-sort: Encapsulate indexed commit information in a sortable object

This eases the comparison and sorting of commits from different heads.

git-sort: Add option to control movement of patches between subsystem sections

Currently, a valid ordering in series.conf may become outdated after a
subsystem repository is merged into an upstream repository. At that point,
a series.conf which passed the validation check in the past would no longer
be accepted because, for example, patches in the "net" section should move
to the "mainline" section. This means that users often have to first
refresh the ordering in series.conf to reflect upstream changes before
adding new patches. In order to reduce the burden on users, make it the
default that patches will remain in their current subsystem section unless
it is explicitely requested to move them to upstream sections. This should
effectively accept an outdated but once-valid ordering.

Fixed locale test in the presence of LANGUAGE

According to GNU documents, the priority order of language variables
is LANGUAGE, LC_ALL, LC_*, LANG. Therefore, if LANGUAGE is set, it
overrides the LC_ALL setting from the test. An empty value is ignored,
and setting it to empty is easier to deal with than just deleting the
variable.

Also fixed the Google translate fail esperanto grammar.

Fixes bug 1235058

Change-Id: Ic97b90dfc21997e19cc473250794a9b3c526beb5

Replace dict.iteritems() with dict.items()

The iteritems() of Python 2 dictionaries has been renamed to items() on
Python 3. According to a discussion on the openstack-dev mailing list,
the overhead of creating a temporary list using dict.items() on Python 2
is very low because most dictionaries are small:

http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-June/066391.html

Patch generated by the following command:

    sed -i 's,iteritems,items,g' \
      $(find swift -name "*.py") \
      $(find test -name "*.py")

Change-Id: I6070bb6c684be76e8e77222a7d280ec6edd43496

monkeypatch thread for keystoneclient

keystoneclient uses threading.Lock(), but swift doesn't
monkeypatch threading, this result in lockup when two
greenthreads try to acquire a non green lock.

This change fixes that.

Added --exec_dir option

The --exec_dir option specifies an alternate directory for the
searchgui distribution.  If the option is used and the directory does
not exist, the script will copy the distribution to that directory.
SearchGui updates files relative to the path of the jar file. Thus we
need to copy the jar file, lib, and resources to the working directory
when used in a multiuser environment such as galaxy.

make: Support spaces in filenames in bundle names.

Part 1. All changes in this CL are covered by tests, leaving out any single
thing makes one of the tests in the tests/mac directory fail.

Changes:

* Replace ' ' with '\ ' for some makefile rules, assert neither name nor
  dependency contains a space in the other cases. I looked at all callers
  of WriteDoCmd() and WriteMakeRule().

* In particular, self.output and self.output_binary always have '\ ' for spaces

* Quote a few things:
+ cmd_link: For app bundles with spaces (e.g. "chromium helper")

Mac/ninja: Add support for prefix headers.

I tried 3 approaches:

1. extra_cflags on cc command, separate pch command
   ( http://codereview.chromium.org/9065001 )
2. override cflags per rule to add -include for source files and -x for gch files
   ( http://codereview.chromium.org/9028003 )
3. have a base_cflags with normal flags, set cflags to $base_cflags -include,
   override it with $base_cflags -x for gch files
    ( http://codereview.chromium.org/9064001/ )

1 is messy but fast. 2 is cleaner but a lot slower (due to cflags per .o file). 3 is cleanish and fast.

1 is what the make generator is doing. I wanted to do something like 2 but couldn't figure out
how to convince make's variable scoping to do that.

3 requires not passing cflags_cc to objcxx invocations (else it gets two -includes),
so instead set cflags_mm to $cflags_cc.

This change implements the general idea of 3., but with the extra_cflags (called cflags_pch) from 1.
Also enable the first test in test/mac for ninja!

Loosely based on a patch from Jeremy Apthorp <jeremya@chromium.org> (approach 1.)

make/mac: Delay space escaping until write time.

self.output and self.output_binary used to contain escaped spaces. Instead,
let WriteMakeRule() escape spaces, WriteDoCmd() now does so by transitivity.
Manually escape spaces in every WriteLn() call.

This gets rid of the awkward escape->unescape in WriteXcodeEnv() and allows
sharing that code with the ninja generator.
